31st March saw the announcement of a Bowie solo exhibition of his art, running from 18th April, to 29th April, 1995, at the Gallery in Cork Street, London. This was to be the first solo exhibition of his work: New Afro Pagan and Work: 1975-1995. More here: https://smarturl.it/BowieAfroPaganDBFB

With a theme of STAY HOME (“David Bowie turned isolation into an art form"), and in celebration of TASCHEN’s reissue of @TheRealMickRock’s superb The Rise of David Bowie 1972-1973, Robin Murray interviews the photographer for Issue #115 of @ClashMagazine - https://smarturl.it/CLASH115BowieRock

As April 16th turns to the 17th, Parlophone are making the 9-track CHANGESNOWBOWIE LP available for streaming: https://lnk.to/DavidBowie-CNB Originally broadcast by the BBC for his 50th birthday in 1997, CHANGESNOWBOWIE features acoustic versions of some of David’s own favourite songs.

The CHANGESBOWIE LP hit the top spot in the UK 30 years ago today, promoted by Bowie’s SOUND + VISION World Tour which kicked off in Canada, on 4th March. It included 16 UK Top 20 hits, of which10 were Top 5 and 6 US Top 20 hits of which 2 made the Top 5. https://smarturl.it/CHANGESBOWIEonDBFB

Melody Maker 28th March, 1970, and Bowie is interviewed for a piece by Raymond Telford, titled: “HYPE AND DAVID BOWIE'S FUTURE”. Two days later a gig at the Star Hotel in West Croydon, would be drummer John Cambridge’s last gig with the band. More here: https://smarturl.it/HypeOverDBFB

Throughout David Bowie’s professional career, Japanese photographer, Masayoshi Sukita, managed to capture an indefinable quality and spirit present in every studio session the two collaborated on. These particular images were taken in New York in 2002. #RandomBowie #BowieSukita

Following its release last Friday, the Is It Any Wonder? EP has entered the UK album chart at #10, This from the @OfficialCharts: “Previously unreleased David Bowie EP Is It Any Wonder? enters at Number 10 following its release on vinyl - the week’s biggest seller on black wax.”

Fame 90 was released as a single in the UK on 26th March 1990, the very day that David Bowie’s SOUND + VISION World Tour continued its globe trot with a 3-day stint at the London Arena. Watch the video over on the official David Bowie YouTube channel now: https://smarturl.it/Fame90VidYT

35 years ago today at Tina Turner's NEC gig in Birmingham, Bowie and Tina performed the songs Tonight and Let’s Dance. The live duet of Tonight was released as a single in 1988, becoming a #1 hit in the Netherlands. Watch it now on Tina’s official YouTube: https://smarturl.it/BowieTurnerTonightYT
